AssertionError: '1.5.3' not found in '# 29 — Three Improvement Axes and Version History\n\n**Source:** `03_DEVELOPMENT_CONTEXT.md` §"Three improvement axes", §"Version history highlights"; `01_README_project.md` §"What\'s new in …"; Cowork 2026-04-03 conversion chat and 2026-04-06 v1.3.7 results review (preserved in `_raw/12_…md`, `_raw/13_…md`).\n\n## Why these exist together\n\nEvery missed bug in QPB\'s history falls on one of three diagnostic axes. The axis a miss lands on tells you *where* to fix the skill. The version history is the record of which axis was being improved in each release — it is the "how QPB learned" log.\n\nThis doc is the condensed form. The full release notes live in `01_README_project.md` §"What\'s new in vX.Y.Z"; this doc frames them in terms of which axis each release attacked.\n\n## The three axes\n\n### 1. Exploration rules — "the agent never looked at the code"\n\n**Symptom.** The bug lives in a file / function / subsystem that Phase 1 exploration never opened. Phase 3 code review can\'t find bugs in code it hasn\'t been shown.\n\n**Where to fix.** Phase 1 exploration patterns in SKILL.md, `references/exploration_patterns.md` (pattern applicability matrix), domain-knowledge questions. Or — add a new **iteration strategy** (see axis 2) that targets the unexplored area.\n\n**Example.** The parity sub-type checklist was added in v1.3.46 to `references/iteration.md` because the parity strategy wasn\'t comparing *resource lifecycle* (setup vs. teardown) — it was only finding "obvious" parallel-path differences. The underlying exploration rule wasn\'t wrong; it was too coarse.\n\n### 2. Iteration types — "the agent looked but no strategy found it"\n\n**Symptom.** The code was explored, but the bug\'s shape doesn\'t match what any existing iteration strategy targets. Baseline structural review can\'t see it; gap and parity don\'t apply; adversarial has nothing to re-examine.\n\n**Where to fix.** Add a new iteration strategy to `references/iteration.md`. Each strategy exists because a specific class of bugs was being systematically missed.\n\n**History of strategy additions:**\n\n| Strategy | Added in | Problem it solved |\n|---|---|---|\n| gap | v1.3.44 | Baseline covered only a subset of the codebase |\n| unfiltered | v1.3.44 | Structured approach over-constrained exploration — zero-bug runs on codebases with known bugs |\n| parity | v1.3.45 / v1.3.40 | No strategy explicitly compared parallel code paths; virtio had transport-parity bugs invisible to subsystem-focused passes |\n| adversarial | v1.3.44 | Conservative triage kept dismissing real bugs; Type-II errors dominated |\n\n### 3. Triage calibration — "the agent found it but dismissed it"\n\n**Symptom.** The bug was flagged as a candidate, made it to triage, and was dismissed as "permissive behavior" or "design choice" or "ambiguous." The exploration was right; the rejection was wrong.\n\n**Where to fix.** Triage rules in SKILL.md (evidentiary standards, "what counts as sufficient evidence"), the Demoted Candidates Manifest in `references/iteration.md` (tracks dismissed findings with re-promotion criteria), adversarial strategy evidentiary bar.\n\n**Example.** Pydantic\'s `AliasPath` bug was found and dismissed **three times** before the adversarial strategy recovered it. Triage kept classifying the permissive behavior as a "design choice" because the behavior was, indeed, permissive. The fix was lowering the adversarial evidentiary bar: **code-path trace + semantic drift is sufficient** — you don\'t need a runtime crash to confirm. See `23_iteration_strategies.md` §"Strategy 4 — `adversarial`".\n\n## Version history highlights\n\nThe condensed list. For full release notes, see `01_README_project.md` §"What\'s new in …".\n\n### v1.3.x — the discovery era\n\n- **v1.3.13–v1.3.14** — Early structured approach. Zero bugs found. Too rigid. This was the motivation for the unfiltered strategy.\n- **v1.3.21** — Gate hardening. First confirmed bugs (2 total across 10 repos). Triage calibration start.\n- **v1.3.25** — Unfiltered domain-driven exploration. **Major breakthrough — 14 bugs.** The structured approach had been the bottleneck.\n- **v1.3.40** — Parity patterns. Found 5 virtio bugs using fallback-path comparison. Iteration-types axis.\n- **v1.3.44** — Iteration mode (gap, unfiltered, adversarial). **3.7x baseline yield.** The multi-strategy architecture.\n- **v1.3.45** — `references/iteration.md` reference file, parity strategy, suggested-next-prompt UX.\n- **v1.3.46** — Demoted Candidates Manifest, parity sub-type checklist, adversarial bar adjustment, TDD execution enforcement.\n- **v1.3.47** — TDD log enforcement — six insertion points from a Cursor diagnostic run. Triage-calibration axis.\n\n### v1.4.x — productization and hardening\n\n- **v1.4.0** (promoted from v1.3.50) — Six-phase interactive architecture, end-of-phase messages, `--phase` flag in runner, quality gate script, four iteration strategies formalized with 40-60% yield boost, TDD enforcement, `references/iteration.md` replaces older `ITERATION.md`, orchestrator agents for Claude Code and Copilot. **Benchmarked against Express.js (14 bugs), Gson (9 bugs), Linux virtio (8 bugs)** — all 100% TDD coverage, 0 gate failures.\n- **v1.4.1** — **Recheck mode**, 19 bug fixes from bootstrap self-audit (eval injection, bash 3.2 empty arrays, required artifacts → WARN, json_key_count false positives, missing-artifact checks). 19/19 recheck-verified FIXED.\n- **v1.4.2** — **25 bug fixes from Sonnet 4.6 bootstrap self-audit** (3 HIGH, 8 MEDIUM, 14 LOW). nullglob-safe artifact detection, severity-prefixed IDs (BUG-H1/M3/L6), TDD sidecar cross-validation, integration enum validation. Run metadata JSON for multi-model comparison. 25/25 recheck-verified FIXED. **Sonnet recommended as default** (25 bugs at ~3% weekly vs Opus 19 bugs at ~8%).\n- **v1.4.3** — **Challenge gate added** for false-positive detection (edgequake: 6/7 "CRITICAL" were documented feature gaps, one was a placeholder). Functional-test reference refactored into single `references/functional_tests.md`.\n- **v1.4.4** — **Orchestrator hardening — "you are the orchestrator" architecture.** Fixes three failure modes from casbin: single-context collapse, `claude -p` subprocess spawning, nested Agent-tool stripping. `references/orchestrator_protocol.md` with inline duplication in each agent file.\n- **v1.4.5** — Runner rewritten in Python (`bin/run_playbook.py` + `bin/benchmark_lib.py`, 36 stdlib-only tests). Positional args are directory paths. **Python gate is sole mechanical gate** (`quality_gate.sh` retired; `quality_gate.py` at `.github/skills/quality_gate/` with 108 unit tests; symlink for stable invocation). **Benchmark set reduced to four targets**: bootstrap, chi, cobra, virtio. Recheck gate fix (root key `bugs` → `results`).\n\n### v1.5.x — self-audit foundations (in progress)\n\n- **v1.5.0** — Formal docs pipeline (tier 1/2 cited in REQ manifest, tier 3/4 context-only), `formal_docs_manifest.json`, `requirements_manifest.json`, `bugs_manifest.json`, citation semantic check.\n- **v1.5.1** (current) — Phases 1–3 operator-flow improvements, Phase 2 observability, Phase 3 invocation flexibility. Phase 5.1 self-audit docs curation (this directory). Phase 5.2 challenge-gate coverage check, Phase 5.3 virtio-1.4.6 fixture preservation, Phase 2.rev/2.3.rev Darwin-banner and PROGRESS.md iteration heartbeats remain outstanding. Phase 4 benchmark validation and Item 5.4 self-audit bootstrap pending.\n\n## Benchmarking discipline\n\n**Bug counts vary between runs.** The same skill on the same codebase produces different bug counts due to non-determinism in exploration. A single run isn\'t definitive. Compare across **5+ runs** or use iteration cycles to compensate.\n\n**Baseline vs. iteration yield.** Baseline typically finds 1–3 bugs per repo. Full iteration cycle (gap + unfiltered + parity + adversarial) multiplies by 3–4x. If a skill change doesn\'t improve baseline yield, it may still improve iteration yield or vice versa — track both.\n\n**Spot-check every new version.** After skill changes, spot-check 3–5 bugs from the new version against actual source code. Verify the bug is real, the file:line is correct, and the regression test would actually fail. v1.3.46: 15/15 spot-checked bugs verified as real.\n\n**Council reviews.** For major skill changes, three different AI agents independently analyze the benchmark data and propose improvements. The agents do not modify code; they write analysis documents. Artifacts live in `council-reviews/` with `COUNCIL_BRIEFING_VN.md`, per-reviewer `{AGENT}_RESPONSE_VN.md`, and prompts explicitly saying "DO NOT modify any code."\n\n## The missed-bug feedback loop\n\nEvery confirmed miss becomes a change to the skill. The loop:\n\n1. A bug is reported (externally — maintainer, benchmark, user) or discovered (retroactively — fresh run with a newer skill catches what an older skill missed).\n2. Classify the miss on the three axes: exploration? iteration type? triage calibration?\n3. The axis determines which file is edited: SKILL.md exploration patterns, `references/iteration.md`, `references/challenge_gate.md`, etc.\n4. Benchmark against ≥2 repos (one large, one small) to validate the change.\n5. Release note in `01_README_project.md` that names the miss and the fix.\n\nThis is why version history is tightly coupled to the three axes: every version note is a diagnostic-to-fix trace.\n\n## Spec-auditor focus\n\n- **Misses should be classified on one of the three axes.** A miss that can\'t be classified is a symptom the axis taxonomy is incomplete.\n- **Version history must trace changes to specific benchmark observations.** Releases that say "improved X" without naming the repo / finding that motivated the change are not auditable.\n- **Baseline and iteration yield are tracked separately.** A change that trades baseline yield for iteration yield (or vice versa) is a real tradeoff, not a regression.\n- **Spot-check rate is a release criterion.** 15/15 real bugs on spot-check is the v1.3.46 floor; releases that don\'t hit similar rates should be flagged.\n- **Council reviews produce analysis, not code changes.** A council review that modifies code has broken protocol.\n\n## What\'s NOT in scope for this doc\n\n- Release notes for versions before v1.3.13 (not retained in current history).\n- Per-agent tuning (see `31_known_limitations.md`).\n- Benchmark isolation protocol (see `30_benchmark_protocol_and_self_audit.md`).\n- Specific fixes in v1.5.0 / v1.5.1 (see `QPB_v1.5.1_Implementation_Plan.md`).\n'

